### Past Critique
- The `pig_latinify` function type signature did not handle an empty vector properly.
- Words without vowels were treated incorrectly; they should not be altered in Pig Latin.

### Critique
- There were no major issues in the code execution as no errors were detected.
- While the current tests cover primary cases, adding more complex tests could help ensure the robustness of the function.

### Improve
- Include challenging test cases that deal with words containing punctuation, mixed-case sentences, and consecutive vowels.
- Add a test case to handle words that end with "y", as these can present unique edge cases in Pig Latin transformation.

```julia
using Base.Threads

# Function definitions remain the same as in the previous improvement

# Unit tests
using Test

@testset "Pig Latin transformation tests" begin
    @test pig_latinify(["hello", "world", "julia", "language"]) == ["ellohay", "orldway", "uliajay", "anguagelay"]
    @test pig_latinify(Vector{String}()) == Vector{String}()
    @test pig_latinify([""]) == [""]
    @test pig_latinify(["Pig", "latin"]) == ["Igpay", "atinlay"]
    @test pig_latinify(["smile"]) == ["ilesmay"]
    @test pig_latinify(["Rhythm"]) == ["Rhythm"]  # Word with no vowels

    # Challenging tests
    @test pig_latinify(["Happy"]) == ["Appyhay"]  # Word ending with "y"
    @test pig_latinify(["'hello'"]) == ["'ellohay'"]  # Word with punctuation
    @test pig_latinify(["eat", "omelet", "are"]) == ["eatyay", "omeletay", "areyay"]  # Consecutive vowels
    @test pig_latinify(["McCloud"]) == ["cCloudMay"]  # Mixed-case non-trivial word
end
```
